# gitleaks fingerprint-level ignore list.
#
# Format: one `<file>:<rule>:<line>:<finding>` fingerprint per line — copy
# from the `Fingerprint:` line in a `gitleaks detect` finding when you
# decide that hit is a real false positive.
#
# Rules of the road (T-061):
#
# 1. NEVER add a bare file path (e.g. `.env.example`) here. That whitelists
#    the entire file forever — including real secrets accidentally pasted
#    later. Use a narrow `regexes = [...]` allowlist entry in `gitleaks.toml`
#    instead so we still catch new secret patterns in the same file.
#
# 2. Every entry below MUST carry a comment explaining WHY it is a false
#    positive (test fixture, vendored snapshot, doc example, etc.). No bare
#    fingerprints — code review will reject them.
#
# 3. Prefer fixing the underlying noise (e.g. swap a real-looking hex tail
#    for `xxxxx...`) over ignoring it. Ignores are forever; nudging a
#    fixture is a one-line edit.
#
# Baseline at T-061 land: empty (no false positives needed an ignore on the
# 2026-05-13 sweep — the only borderline matches were carve-outs already
# covered by `gitleaks.toml` allowlist regexes).
